  "script": "40 million people, one storm? A massive severe-weather threat is lighting up the Midwest, and the numbers are ugly: from Kansas City to Chicago, around 40 million people sit in the path of the same system. Forecasters are warning about destructive winds over 70 miles an hour, hail the size of tennis balls, and the real fear — strong, fast-moving tornadoes. Some areas could get hit by round after round of storms, stacking up flash-flood risk on top of everything else. This is the kind of setup where the sky goes green and the warnings come faster than people can react. Millions are being told one thing: have a way to get the alert, tonight. So when the siren actually goes off, where exactly do you go?",
